AB  - There exists an interesting intersection of political reality in the United States among blacks, Latinos, and whites. This political reality stems from behaviors within the American political economic system which manifest in inequity. This study examines the impact of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 on the Black and Latino unemployment. This study is based on the premise that Blacks and Latinos were negatively affected by the Great Recession and its economic phenomenon. A case study impact analysis approach is used to draw conclusions from the data gathered from government documents obtained from the Bureau of Labor Statistics for the United States as a whole and the cities of Atlanta, Georgia, and Los Angeles, California. The authors found that during the Great Recession Black and Latino rates of unemployment were as severe as national unemployment during the early years of the Great Depression, yet the Act was focused on macro-economic issues versus micro-economic employment rates found among Black and Latino communities.
